1️⃣ What is Active Directory?
🔹 Active Directory (AD)

A Microsoft directory service that stores:

Users

Groups

Roles

Permissions

Computers

It is used for:

Authentication (Who are you?)

Authorization (What can you access?)

2️⃣ What is Group / Role Mapping?

When using SAML:

AD = Identity Provider (IdP)

Rails app = Service Provider (SP)

User logs in via AD → AD sends SAML response → Rails receives it.

Inside the SAML response, AD sends:

User attributes (email, name)

Group memberships

Example attributes in SAML:

<Attribute Name="email">
  <AttributeValue>shubham@company.com</AttributeValue>
</Attribute>

<Attribute Name="groups">
  <AttributeValue>Admins</AttributeValue>
  <AttributeValue>Instructors</AttributeValue>
</Attribute>

Now your Rails app must map these AD groups to internal roles.

That mapping is called:

🔹 Active Directory group/role mapping

3️⃣ Why Do We Need Mapping?

Because:

AD group names ≠ Rails role names (always)

Example:

AD Group	Rails Role
AD_Admins	admin
AD_Coordinators	coordinator
AD_Instructors	instructor

Your app must translate AD groups → internal roles.

4️⃣ How This Works in Rails (Step-by-Step)
Step 1: User logs in via SAML

You use:

ruby-saml

devise_saml_authenticatable

Step 2: Rails receives SAML response
response = OneLogin::RubySaml::Response.new(params[:SAMLResponse])
Step 3: Extract groups
groups = response.attributes['groups']

Now suppose:

groups = ["AD_Admins", "AD_Instructors"]
5️⃣ Mapping Logic in Rails

You create mapping logic:

GROUP_ROLE_MAPPING = {
  "AD_Admins" => "admin",
  "AD_Coordinators" => "coordinator",
  "AD_Instructors" => "instructor"
}

Then:

roles = groups.map { |g| GROUP_ROLE_MAPPING[g] }.compact

Then assign roles:

user.roles = roles
user.save!
6️⃣ Real-World Example (Your Learn Module App)

You mentioned your app has:

courses

programs

users

enrollments

roles

admins

coordinators

instructors

Now imagine:

AD Groups:
AD Group	Meaning
LMS_Admins	Full access
LMS_Coordinators	Manage programs
LMS_Instructors	Manage courses

Your Rails logic:

case group
when "LMS_Admins"
  user.add_role(:admin)
when "LMS_Coordinators"
  user.add_role(:coordinator)
when "LMS_Instructors"
  user.add_role(:instructor)
end

Now:

✔️ AD controls access centrally
✔️ Rails app automatically assigns correct roles

This is enterprise-level SSO architecture.

7️⃣ Important Things Interviewers Expect You to Know
✅ 1. Groups come via SAML attributes
✅ 2. Mapping is done at application level
✅ 3. Handle multiple groups
✅ 4. Handle default role if no group matches
✅ 5. Remove roles if group removed (important!)

Example safe approach:

user.roles = mapped_roles

Instead of:

user.add_role(...)

Otherwise old roles remain forever.

8️⃣ Edge Cases (Very Important for Interviews)
🔹 What if no group attribute is sent?

→ Reject login or assign default role

🔹 What if user belongs to multiple groups?

→ Assign highest privilege role (define priority)

🔹 What if AD group renamed?

→ Mapping breaks → user loses access

🔹 What if user removed from group in AD?

→ Next login → roles updated automatically

9️⃣ How To Debug Group Mapping Issues

Log full SAML attributes:

Rails.logger.info response.attributes.inspect

Verify group attribute name:

Sometimes it's memberOf

Sometimes it's a long URI

Confirm IdP metadata includes group attribute

🔟 Advanced Enterprise Concept

Sometimes instead of SAML groups, AD sends:

role

department

title

And mapping logic is based on those attributes.

Example:

if response.attributes['department'] == "IT"
  user.add_role(:admin)
end
🎯 How To Say This in Interview (Perfect Answer)

If interviewer asks:

Are you familiar with Active Directory group/role mapping?

You can say:

Yes. In SAML-based authentication, the IdP like Active Directory sends user group memberships as attributes in the SAML response. In our Rails application, we extract those group attributes and map them to internal roles such as admin, coordinator, or instructor. We maintain a mapping configuration and assign roles dynamically on login. We also ensure roles are updated or removed if group membership changes.

